```

---

## 12. Build and Run

- Development: run the Express server and Vite dev server together using pnpm workspaces. Configure Vite to proxy `/api` requests to the Express server so there are no CORS issues in development.
- Production: build the React app with Vite, then serve the static `dist` folder from the Express server. All requests to `/api` are handled by Express. All other requests serve `index.html` for client-side routing.
- Start command for hosting: `pnpm build && pnpm start`
- **Historical backfill (Docker Compose):** When the stack is running via Docker Compose, use the server container as the standard way to run backfill — same env and dependencies as the app. Example: `docker compose exec server pnpm --filter server backfill --days=7` (adjust `--days=` as needed). Do not default to host-only `pnpm backfill` when Compose is up unless there is a specific reason.

---

## 13. Notes for the Developer — Things Likely to Go Wrong

This section exists to prevent common implementation mistakes. Read all of it before writing any code.

**Two separate card components, not one**
Today's Feed and History use different card layouts. Build two separate components — a `CompanyCard` for Today's Feed and a `NewsCard` for History. Do not build one card component and try to handle both layouts with props or conditional logic. They are genuinely different UI patterns.

**The expand/collapse "See more" is local state only**
When a company card on Today's Feed has more than 5 items and the analyst clicks "See more", this expands the card inline. It is a local `useState` toggle within the `CompanyCard` component. It does not navigate to another page, does not make an API call, and does not require any routing logic. All items are already in memory from the initial fetch — just show or hide the ones beyond 5.

**Never hardcode company names in the frontend**
The company filter buttons on both pages must be derived dynamically from whatever companies appear in the data returned by the API. Do not hardcode CrowdStrike, Microsoft, or Palo Alto Networks anywhere in the frontend. On a day where only one company has news, only that company's button plus All should appear.

**Each headline inside a company card needs its own date**
On Today's Feed, each company card contains a list of headlines. Each individual headline in that list must show its own publication date next to it (e.g. `Apr 8, 2026` in small grey text). Do not only show one date on the card header. Analysts need to distinguish between items that may have been published at different times.

**Order company cards by most recently updated**
When All is selected on Today's Feed, company cards must be ordered by the date of each company's most recent news item, newest first. Do not render them in the order the API returns them, which may be arbitrary.

**Source links must open in a new tab safely**
Every source link must include both `target="_blank"` and `rel="noopener noreferrer"`. Missing the rel attribute is a security vulnerability. Missing target="_blank" means the analyst loses their place in the app. Both attributes are required on every link.

**Date separators in History require grouping, not a library**
In History, insert a styled date label (e.g. `April 7, 2026`) between groups of cards from different days. Implement this by sorting all items by date descending, then grouping them by date in JavaScript before rendering. Iterate over the groups and render a separator label before each new date group. No third-party library is needed for this.

**Apply Newsreader font only to page-level headings**
Inter is the default font for everything in the app. Newsreader serif is applied only to the main `h1` page headings — the "Good morning. Here is your client news briefing." heading on Today's Feed and the "News History" heading on History. Do not apply Newsreader to card headlines, sidebar text, buttons, or any other element.

**Show a loading state when the History toggle changes**
The History page fetches from the API both on initial load and whenever the analyst switches between 14 days and 30 days. Each time the toggle changes, show a loading state immediately and clear the previous results while the new fetch is in progress. Do not leave the old data visible while the new data loads — this will confuse analysts into thinking the toggle did nothing.

**Convert the last refreshed timestamp to Eastern time**
The `last_updated` value from Supabase is stored in UTC. When displaying it as "Last refreshed today at 8:04 AM", convert it to US Eastern time before formatting. Use `toLocaleTimeString('en-US', { timeZone: 'America/New_York', hour: '2-digit', minute: '2-digit' })`. Displaying the raw UTC time will show 1:00 PM instead of 8:00 AM and will confuse users.

---

## 14. Source Link Integrity

This is a product requirement, not just a code note. Every `sourceUrl` in the data must point to a real, specific article page. The Gemini prompt must be written to enforce this. During development, manually verify that a sample of generated URLs actually resolve to the correct article before shipping. If a URL returns a 404 or redirects to a homepage, the prompt needs to be adjusted.
